We observe a pattern that can simplify each term in the series. For any integer $n \geq 2$, we can write $\frac{n-1}{n!}$ as a difference of two fractions:
$$\frac{n-1}{n!} = \frac{1}{(n-1)!} - \frac{1}{n!}.$$

Using this identity, we rewrite the terms of the series:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2!} + \frac{2}{3!} + \frac{3}{4!} + \ldots + \frac{2015}{2016!}
&= \left(\frac{1}{1!} - \frac{1}{2!}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{2!} - \frac{1}{3!}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{3!} - \frac{1}{4!}\right) + \ldots + \left(\frac{1}{2015!} - \frac{1}{2016!}\right).
\end{align*}

When we sum the series, most terms cancel out due to the telescoping nature of the series:
\begin{align*}
\text{(Series)} &= \frac{1}{1!} - \frac{1}{2!} + \frac{1}{2!} - \frac{1}{3!} + \ldots + \frac{1}{2015!} - \frac{1}{2016!} \\
&= 1 - \frac{1}{2016!}.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the sum we are looking for is given by
$$ \boxed{1 - \frac{1}{2016!}}. $$

